$NVDA NVIDIA reported strong Q1 financial results, surpassing expectations with earnings of $1.09 per share, $0.17 higher than anticipated. Although revenues declined by 13.2% YoY to $7.19 billion, they exceeded the expected $6.52 billion. Gaming revenue was $2.24 billion, up 22% from the previous quarter despite a 38% YoY decline. Professional Visualization revenue reached $295 million, up 31% from the previous quarter, while Automotive revenue grew by 1% to a record $296 million. NVIDIA's optimistic guidance for Q2 projects revenues of $11.0 billion, well above the expected $7.11 billion. $UBSFY Analyst Richard Eary commented, "Post a 30% re-rate into FY23 results, we downgrade Ubisoft to Sell and cut our earnings and DCF PT to €20 (from €55). At current prices, we believe the market is pricing in Ubisoft's ability to fully execute on its FY24 guidance while delivering materially higher LT cash margins incl. SBC (>25% vs. FY19 peak of 14%). Material risks exist in our view based on past execution (UBSe 6% below FY24 non-IFRS EBIT guidance). FY24 guidance will require Ubisoft to successfully deliver the biggest front book revenue performance in its history despite expecting back catalogue to decline post a poor FY23 release slate and a soft consumer backdrop. Moreover, FCF generation remains poor (negative in 5 of the last 10 yrs) and on our estimates will only turn FCF positive in FY26 assuming full cost out execution (€200m by FY26). Also, while sector M&A is elevated, we believe the agreement with Tencent in Sept-22 limits options. The Ubisoft forward is on 12 June." Bearish

Citi's Paul Lejuez commented, "We are upgrading $GPS from Sell to Neutral. While we anticipate 1Q sales results ( AMC 5/25) will be below consensus (comps -4% vs cons -2%) and believe 2Q trends are running below cons, sentiment is extremely negative. Old Navy's consumer is likely feeling the recent pressures seen throughout retail and we believe the once darling Athleta brand is struggling with brand-specific issues that likely won't get fixed in F23. However, tailwinds in GM (freight, lean inventory, lapping promos) and cost-cutting opportunities should limit EPS downside relative to our new F23E. We are below cons on 2Q sales (-6% vs cons -5%) but above on EPS ($0.21 vs cons $0.18). With the CEO seat still empty (after almost a year), uncertainty is high. However, shares are trading at 3-year lows and an F23E EV/EBITDA multiple of 4.0x, accounting for significant uncertainty, and suggesting a more balanced risk/reward." Bullish
